{{Hinduism by country}}
{{Azerbaijanis}}

'''Hinduism in Azerbaijan''' has been tied to [[cultural diffusion]] on the [[Silk Road]].  One of the remnants of once-dominant [[Hinduism|Hindu]] and [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] culture in the [[Caucasus]] is [[Suraxanı raion|Surakhani]], the site of the [[Ateshgah of Baku]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20040219010934/http://sify.com/news/international/fullstory.php?id=13267652 Rare Hindu temple in Muslim Azerbaijan] - Sify.com</ref>

==History==
In the [[Middle Ages]], Hindu traders visited present-day [[Azerbaijan]] for [[Silk Road]] trade.  The area was traversed by Hindu traders coming mostly from [[Multan]] and [[Sindh]] (in present-day Pakistan).  The [[Ateshgah of Baku|Atasghah]] in [[Suraxanı raion|Surakhani]] was used by those traders to worship while in the area.  Most of the traders left around the advent of the [[British Raj]].  The ceremonies were officiated by a [[Punjabi people|Punjabi]] [[pandit]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070311003705/http://www.nchtuk.org/content.php?id=218 Pre – Islamic Vedic Culture in Afghanistan] - NHCTUK</ref>  Historical sources indicate that locals worshipped at Surakhani even before the construction of the Atashgah, drawn by the "seven holes with burning flame" from which Surakhani takes its name.<ref>[http://azeri.org/Azeri/az_latin/manuscripts/land_of_fire/english/112_observations_farid.html Observations from the Ancients] Farid Bakharov - Azerbaijan International</ref> In the 1880s, the Czar [[Alexander III of Russia]] went to Azerbaijan to witness one of the last Hindu ceremonies performed there.  After the 1890s, nearly all of the original Hindu merchants in Azerbaijan had died or left for The Indian Subcontinent.<ref>[http://www.avesta.org/modi/baku.htm My Travels Outside Bombay] - Ervad Shams-Ul-Ulama Dr. Sir Jivanji Jamshedji Modi
B. A., Ph. D. C. I. E.</ref>

==ISKCON==
Members of the [[International Society for Krishna Consciousness]] (ISKCON), also known as the Hare Krishnas, are registered in Baku.<ref>[http://www.eurasianet.org/resource/azerbaijan/hypermail/200204/0018.shtml Azerbaijan Daily Digest]</ref> In October 2002, authorities returned 20,000 of the 35,000 books seized in 1996 from the Baku Society of Krishna Consciousness <ref>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2003/24344.htm Azerbaijan<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> ''Azerbaijan Daily Digest'' states that very few [[Azeri people]] have become Hare Krishna<ref>[http://www.eurasianet.org/resource/azerbaijan/hypermail/200108/0101.html Azerbaijan moves to impose tighter control] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070716222114/http://www.eurasianet.org/resource/azerbaijan/hypermail/200108/0101.html |date=16 July 2007 }} - Eurasian net</ref> and they are mostly represented by members of [[ISKCON]].<ref>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2006/71368.htm International Religious Freedom Report 2006, Azerbaijan] - U.S. State Department</ref>

